
[1]sear

   SEAR, v. t. [Gr. to dry; to parch; dry. L. torreo, in a diffrent
   dialect.]

   1. To burn to dryness and hardness the surface of any thing; to
   cauterize; to expose to a degree of heat that changes the color of the
   surface, ar makes it hard; as, to sear the skin or flesh.

   I'm sear'd with burning steel. Rowe.
